1
00:00:02,753 --> 00:00:04,755
[rhythmic beeping]

2
00:00:07,257 --> 00:00:09,259
[slurping]

3
00:00:20,729 --> 00:00:22,439
[slurping]

4
00:00:58,016 --> 00:01:00,018
[phone ringing]

5
00:01:05,858 --> 00:01:07,860
[phone ringing]

6
00:01:16,285 --> 00:01:18,620
-Hello?
-[Laxmi] <i>How dare you make my son cry.</i>

7
00:01:19,329 --> 00:01:20,247
Laxmi?

8
00:01:20,330 --> 00:01:21,624
You made everyone cry.

9
00:01:21,707 --> 00:01:24,627
And you gave your chaperone
a heart attack. What is wrong with you?

10
00:01:24,710 --> 00:01:28,464
First of all, I don't have a chaperone,
so stop calling her that.

11
00:01:28,547 --> 00:01:31,675
Second of all, Zosia's gonna be fine,
thank you for asking.

12
00:01:31,758 --> 00:01:34,220
-<i>And third of all...</i>
-Why do you do such things?

13
00:01:34,303 --> 00:01:35,513
Are you mentally unsound?

14
00:01:35,596 --> 00:01:40,100
Third of all... [inhales deeply]
...I learned something important.

15
00:01:40,684 --> 00:01:42,269
Laxmi, I think that
there might be a way to fix...

16
00:01:42,352 --> 00:01:45,147
You do not ever make my son cry again.

17
00:01:45,230 --> 00:01:46,986
-[hang-up beep]
-[breathes heavily]

18
00:01:53,572 --> 00:01:56,033
Hey, if Miss Sunshine asks
for my phone number again,

19
00:01:56,116 --> 00:01:57,618
you tell her to pound sand.

20
00:02:17,179 --> 00:02:18,935
She's gonna be all right, isn't she?

21
00:02:19,848 --> 00:02:21,058
She's gonna be fine.

22
00:02:58,762 --> 00:02:59,888
[exhales deeply]

23
00:03:34,965 --> 00:03:36,967
[dreamy music playing]

24
00:04:43,325 --> 00:04:44,326
[music stops]

25
00:04:55,337 --> 00:04:56,463
[inhales sharply]

26
00:05:04,888 --> 00:05:05,931
[clears throat]

27
00:05:09,268 --> 00:05:10,269
[groans]

28
00:05:35,836 --> 00:05:36,879
Hello?

29
00:05:53,187 --> 00:05:54,646
Anybody here?

30
00:05:57,816 --> 00:05:59,068
[line ringing]

31
00:05:59,151 --> 00:06:00,236
-[man on phone] <i>Hello, Carol.</i>
-Hey.

32
00:06:00,319 --> 00:06:02,988
-Uh, where-where did everybody...
-<i>This is a recording.</i>

33
00:06:03,071 --> 00:06:06,992
<i>At the tone, you can leave a message
to request anything you might need.</i>

34
00:06:07,075 --> 00:06:08,660
<i>We'll do our best to provide it.</i>

35
00:06:09,536 --> 00:06:12,540
<i>Our feelings for you
haven't changed, Carol.</i>

36
00:06:12,623 --> 00:06:16,543
<i>But after everything that's happened,
we just need a little space.</i>

37
00:06:17,753 --> 00:06:18,921
[phone beeps]

38
00:06:42,778 --> 00:06:45,197
[breathing heavily]

39
00:06:51,495 --> 00:06:53,539
[breathing heavily]

40
00:07:18,355 --> 00:07:19,356
Oh, come on.

41
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:40,169
Are you fucking kidding me?

42
00:07:44,047 --> 00:07:45,048
Fine.

43
00:07:46,800 --> 00:07:48,218
{\an8}Good riddance!

44
00:07:50,762 --> 00:07:51,889
{\an8}Fuck you!

45
00:07:54,933 --> 00:07:56,935
[theme song playing]

46
00:08:44,650 --> 00:08:47,486
Afflicted... Afflicted people.

47
00:09:04,419 --> 00:09:05,420
[camera beeps]

48
00:09:39,496 --> 00:09:41,915
[mumbles]

49
00:09:45,502 --> 00:09:47,171
[clears throat]

50
00:09:55,012 --> 00:09:56,138
[inhales deeply]

51
00:09:56,805 --> 00:10:00,434
To my 12 fellow survivors, greetings.

52
00:10:00,517 --> 00:10:02,186
I'm Carol Sturka.

53
00:10:02,269 --> 00:10:05,272
Some of you know me.
Some of you I've yet to meet.

54
00:10:05,856 --> 00:10:07,024
But...

55
00:10:07,900 --> 00:10:09,266
if you're still one of us...

56
00:10:10,444 --> 00:10:12,070
then this message is for you.

57
00:10:14,823 --> 00:10:17,576
There is a way to undo this situation.

58
00:10:18,243 --> 00:10:21,413
To turn the world back
the way it's supposed to be.

59
00:10:24,499 --> 00:10:25,501
How do I know this?

60
00:10:26,001 --> 00:10:28,421
Because earlier today,

61
00:10:28,504 --> 00:10:33,759
these afflicted people, these Others,
they basically told me so themselves.

62
00:10:34,510 --> 00:10:38,555
Because guess what? They can't lie.

63
00:10:40,098 --> 00:10:42,147
Which is yet another thing
I've discovered.

64
00:10:42,809 --> 00:10:45,438
This alien virus, or... [stammers]

65
00:10:45,521 --> 00:10:49,733
...whatever it is,
it doesn't allow them to do that.

66
00:10:51,068 --> 00:10:55,280
So, what is this solution exactly?

67
00:10:56,240 --> 00:10:58,325
[clicks tongue] That they didn't tell me.

68
00:10:58,992 --> 00:11:05,415
But-But they so resisted telling me,
that everybody suddenly burst into tears.

69
00:11:06,083 --> 00:11:08,460
Worldwide, apparently.

70
00:11:09,545 --> 00:11:11,447
Which I know upset at least one of you.

71
00:11:12,005 --> 00:11:16,844
And then after that, they completely
abandoned the city I live in.

72
00:11:17,970 --> 00:11:20,264
Leaving me here all alone.

73
00:11:21,765 --> 00:11:24,184
Which says to me I'm on the right track.

74
00:11:25,853 --> 00:11:29,857
Now, I realize some of you

75
00:11:30,774 --> 00:11:33,151
think the world might be
better off this way,

76
00:11:33,735 --> 00:11:36,488
with all the newfound peace,
love and understanding.

77
00:11:37,656 --> 00:11:39,116
Enjoy that opinion.

78
00:11:40,200 --> 00:11:41,285
Relish it.

79
00:11:42,077 --> 00:11:44,370
Because it may be
the last one you ever possess.

80
00:11:44,913 --> 00:11:46,332
And when the day comes

81
00:11:46,415 --> 00:11:49,585
that you have peace and love
forced upon you, who knows,

82
00:11:49,668 --> 00:11:51,837
maybe in that last fleeting moment

83
00:11:52,796 --> 00:11:56,633
you might just realize
you treasured your individuality.

84
00:11:58,886 --> 00:12:01,388
Please, let's work together.

85
00:12:02,431 --> 00:12:03,432
The 13 of us.

86
00:12:03,932 --> 00:12:06,030
'Cause it's gonna take
everything we've got.

87
00:12:06,852 --> 00:12:10,063
But these people need saving.

88
00:12:12,816 --> 00:12:14,234
We owe it to humanity.

89
00:12:16,778 --> 00:12:20,657
Call me anytime, day or night.
[inhales deeply]

90
00:12:21,283 --> 00:12:22,618
Good luck and godspeed.

91
00:12:22,701 --> 00:12:23,952
[clears throat]

92
00:12:25,204 --> 00:12:26,205
[camera beeps]

93
00:12:40,385 --> 00:12:41,595
[line ringing]

94
00:12:43,013 --> 00:12:44,432
[automated voice] <i>Hello, Carol.</i>

95
00:12:44,515 --> 00:12:46,016
<i>This is a recording.</i>

96
00:12:46,642 --> 00:12:50,438
<i>At the tone, you can leave a message
to request anything you might need.</i>

97
00:12:50,521 --> 00:12:53,149
-Yes, yes. Mm-hmm.
-<i>We'll do our best to provide it.</i>

98
00:12:53,232 --> 00:12:54,608
-<i>Our feelings for you...</i>
-Got it.

99
00:12:54,691 --> 00:12:56,068
-<i>...haven't changed, Carol.</i>
-Got it.

100
00:12:56,151 --> 00:12:57,987
-Got it.
-<i>But after everything that's happened...</i>

101
00:12:58,070 --> 00:13:00,614
-Hmm. Got it.
-<i>...we just need a little space.</i>

102
00:13:01,573 --> 00:13:02,491
[line beeps]

103
00:13:02,574 --> 00:13:03,868
It's Carol.

104
00:13:03,951 --> 00:13:05,452
I've made a video.

105
00:13:05,994 --> 00:13:07,163
You're not gonna like it.

106
00:13:07,246 --> 00:13:09,707
However, I want you to make 12 copies

107
00:13:09,790 --> 00:13:12,835
and distribute them
to all of the other people like me.

108
00:13:12,918 --> 00:13:14,336
And for those that don't speak English,

109
00:13:14,419 --> 00:13:18,006
I want you to subtitle what I say
word-for-word.

110
00:13:19,424 --> 00:13:20,760
I certainly can't force you to do this.

111
00:13:20,843 --> 00:13:24,847
However, you doing it would please me,
and I know you're into that.

112
00:13:26,473 --> 00:13:29,601
And conversely, if you don't do it,

113
00:13:30,686 --> 00:13:33,314
I can't be held responsible
for the biblically shitty mood

114
00:13:33,397 --> 00:13:35,440
in which I will no doubt find myself.

115
00:13:36,984 --> 00:13:41,488
So, I'm gonna leave it outside
on the curb, by a rock.

116
00:13:42,281 --> 00:13:45,951
And I'll stay far, far away
'cause God knows you need your space.

117
00:14:03,969 --> 00:14:05,429
[breathes deeply]

118
00:14:16,815 --> 00:14:18,483
[mechanical whirring]

119
00:14:52,851 --> 00:14:54,353
[sighs]

120
00:15:20,712 --> 00:15:23,131
[soft music playing]

121
00:15:43,193 --> 00:15:44,403
[grunts]

122
00:15:45,237 --> 00:15:47,447
[breathes deeply]

123
00:16:00,586 --> 00:16:01,587
[smacks lips]

124
00:16:13,432 --> 00:16:14,433
[sighs]

125
00:16:17,227 --> 00:16:19,229
[object rattles]

126
00:16:20,856 --> 00:16:21,940
[sighs]

127
00:16:58,852 --> 00:17:01,855
-[wolves snuffling]
-No. No. No, no, no.

128
00:17:10,113 --> 00:17:12,532
[snuffling continues]

129
00:17:23,085 --> 00:17:24,086
Hey!

130
00:17:26,255 --> 00:17:27,506
Get out of here!

131
00:17:34,429 --> 00:17:35,430
[rustling stops]

132
00:18:07,713 --> 00:18:08,964
[line ringing]

133
00:18:09,631 --> 00:18:11,175
-[automated voice] <i>Hello, Carol.</i>
-[sighs]

134
00:18:11,258 --> 00:18:12,718
<i>This is a recording.</i>

135
00:18:13,343 --> 00:18:16,889
<i>At the tone, you can leave a message
to request anything you might need.</i>

136
00:18:17,472 --> 00:18:20,017
-<i>We'll do our best to provide it.</i>
-[sighs]

137
00:18:20,100 --> 00:18:22,394
<i>Our feelings for you
haven't changed, Carol.</i>

138
00:18:23,061 --> 00:18:26,565
<i>But after everything that's happened,
we just need a little space.</i>

139
00:18:26,648 --> 00:18:28,817
-[smacks lips]
-[phone beeps]

140
00:18:29,484 --> 00:18:32,446
I want the lights back on. All of them.

141
00:18:33,280 --> 00:18:34,281
Everywhere.

142
00:18:34,948 --> 00:18:36,158
Now.

143
00:18:47,294 --> 00:18:48,337
[sighs]

144
00:19:07,231 --> 00:19:09,691
[sighs]

145
00:19:38,011 --> 00:19:39,680
[line ringing]

146
00:19:39,763 --> 00:19:41,390
[automated voice] <i>Hello, Carol.</i>

147
00:19:41,473 --> 00:19:43,267
<i>This is a recording.</i>

148
00:19:43,350 --> 00:19:47,229
<i>At the tone, you can leave a message
to request anything you might need.</i>

149
00:19:47,771 --> 00:19:49,398
<i>We'll do our best to provide it.</i>

150
00:19:50,023 --> 00:19:53,068
<i>Our feelings for you
haven't changed, Carol.</i>

151
00:19:53,151 --> 00:19:56,864
<i>But after everything that's happened,
we just need a little space.</i>

152
00:19:58,448 --> 00:19:59,449
[phone beeps]

153
00:19:59,950 --> 00:20:01,577
I need my trash picked up.

154
00:20:20,095 --> 00:20:22,097
[phone rings]

155
00:20:31,273 --> 00:20:32,274
Hello.

156
00:20:32,858 --> 00:20:34,370
[automated voice] <i>Hello, Carol.</i>

157
00:20:34,735 --> 00:20:35,944
<i>This is a recording.</i>

158
00:20:36,987 --> 00:20:39,657
<i>We can pick up your trash
as long as it's bagged,</i>

159
00:20:39,740 --> 00:20:42,367
<i>and each bag weighs 17 pounds or less.</i>

160
00:20:42,993 --> 00:20:44,662
<i>Please remove all bags from the bin</i>

161
00:20:44,745 --> 00:20:47,998
<i>and place them on the curb
a minimum of two feet apart.</i>

162
00:20:48,081 --> 00:20:49,708
-<i>Thank you.</i>
-[line disconnects]

163
00:21:18,904 --> 00:21:20,906
[drone whirring]

164
00:21:26,286 --> 00:21:27,287
[smacks lips]

165
00:22:22,968 --> 00:22:24,636
[drone grinding]

166
00:22:29,224 --> 00:22:31,393
[drone whirring]

167
00:22:34,646 --> 00:22:35,856
[drone powers off]

168
00:23:27,991 --> 00:23:29,910
[lid clangs]

169
00:23:54,726 --> 00:23:55,727
[sniffs]

170
00:23:57,771 --> 00:23:58,772
[grunts]

171
00:24:10,367 --> 00:24:11,743
[grunts, huffs]

172
00:24:13,120 --> 00:24:14,538
[huffing]

173
00:24:17,875 --> 00:24:18,834
[yelps]

174
00:24:18,917 --> 00:24:20,627
[thuds]

175
00:24:27,885 --> 00:24:29,011
[sighs]

176
00:24:30,012 --> 00:24:32,055
You motherfuckers sure love your milk.

177
00:24:33,182 --> 00:24:34,558
[sighs]

178
00:24:56,872 --> 00:24:59,374
[mysterious music playing]

179
00:26:02,729 --> 00:26:03,730
[sniffs]

180
00:26:05,524 --> 00:26:06,817
[object clatters]

181
00:26:09,152 --> 00:26:11,154
[music continues]

182
00:26:21,832 --> 00:26:22,916
Hello!

183
00:26:26,753 --> 00:26:28,047
[door creaking]

184
00:26:28,130 --> 00:26:30,215
[rustling]

185
00:26:31,842 --> 00:26:32,843
Hello?

186
00:26:34,887 --> 00:26:36,889
[rustling continues]

187
00:26:40,142 --> 00:26:42,186
-[crows cawing]
-[music fades]

188
00:26:43,812 --> 00:26:45,355
-Shoo! Hey!
-[caws]

189
00:26:45,856 --> 00:26:47,399
Shoo! Get out of there!

190
00:26:48,692 --> 00:26:50,861
[cawing]

191
00:26:58,243 --> 00:26:59,536
[crunching]

192
00:27:29,775 --> 00:27:31,777
[industrious music playing]

193
00:27:56,969 --> 00:27:58,846
{\an8}-Greetings, fellow survivors.
-[music stops]

194
00:27:58,929 --> 00:28:01,098
Carol Sturka here with an update.

195
00:28:01,181 --> 00:28:03,809
Here where I live,
Albuquerque, New Mexico,

196
00:28:04,476 --> 00:28:07,646
{\an8}they drink this
like it's going out of style.

197
00:28:07,729 --> 00:28:10,941
Th-These are little milk cartons,

198
00:28:11,024 --> 00:28:13,443
the kind we give children
in elementary schools.

199
00:28:13,944 --> 00:28:15,700
Back when we had elementary schools.

200
00:28:16,071 --> 00:28:17,198
And children.

201
00:28:17,281 --> 00:28:20,534
And, as you can see,
they seem to come in all kinds of flavors.

202
00:28:20,617 --> 00:28:23,204
Plain, chocolate, strawberry, so on.

203
00:28:23,287 --> 00:28:24,580
But the thing is,

204
00:28:25,497 --> 00:28:27,749
it's not milk in any of them.

205
00:28:29,293 --> 00:28:35,382
It is this one strange liquid.

206
00:28:39,094 --> 00:28:42,598
And they make it
in this local dairy facility in my town.

207
00:28:42,681 --> 00:28:44,975
Well, made. Past tense.

208
00:28:45,058 --> 00:28:46,936
'Cause as I told you in my previous video,

209
00:28:47,019 --> 00:28:49,688
they've shut everything down here
and abandoned me completely.

210
00:28:49,771 --> 00:28:52,817
Which is... You know, whatever. Who cares?

211
00:28:52,900 --> 00:28:57,654
But in this dairy,
they make this by mixing water

212
00:28:58,238 --> 00:28:59,281
into...

213
00:29:01,033 --> 00:29:07,164
this #D1AD2C powdery stuff.

214
00:29:07,247 --> 00:29:08,457
Can you see that?

215
00:29:08,540 --> 00:29:10,042
Whatever that is.

216
00:29:10,626 --> 00:29:13,504
And then the resulting liquid is
all they seem to consume.

217
00:29:14,713 --> 00:29:16,089
Look around where you live.

218
00:29:16,590 --> 00:29:20,428
I'll bet they are manufacturing
this in every city in the world.

219
00:29:20,511 --> 00:29:24,306
Everywhere there's a spare dairy
or a... a bottling factory.

220
00:29:24,806 --> 00:29:27,059
Maybe where you are, it doesn't come
in a carton, it comes in a can,

221
00:29:27,142 --> 00:29:29,520
but either way, it's this.

222
00:29:31,730 --> 00:29:32,814
So what is this?

223
00:29:35,234 --> 00:29:37,570
What does it do to them
when they drink it?

224
00:29:37,653 --> 00:29:40,864
Could it be that this is
how they're all staying connected?

225
00:29:42,950 --> 00:29:44,243
Here's what I know so far.

226
00:29:44,326 --> 00:29:45,327
[sniffs]

227
00:29:45,410 --> 00:29:47,120
It does not smell like anything.

228
00:29:48,622 --> 00:29:52,835
But it's got this weird texture.

229
00:29:55,003 --> 00:29:58,090
It's kind of like olive oil, but thinner.

230
00:29:58,590 --> 00:30:00,053
That probably means something.

231
00:30:01,301 --> 00:30:03,846
And I've got no idea
what makes it this color.

232
00:30:03,929 --> 00:30:05,764
What would you call that? Amber?

233
00:30:06,640 --> 00:30:07,891
Straw? Straw colored?

234
00:30:08,559 --> 00:30:11,562
And I tested the pH. It is a... a 7.1,

235
00:30:11,645 --> 00:30:12,938
which means...

236
00:30:13,021 --> 00:30:14,731
Hang on, I have it marked.

237
00:30:15,274 --> 00:30:16,275
It is

238
00:30:17,484 --> 00:30:18,485
neutral.

239
00:30:19,528 --> 00:30:21,655
Well, basically, it's neutral.

240
00:30:22,990 --> 00:30:24,200
You know what else is neutral?

241
00:30:24,283 --> 00:30:25,367
Celery.

242
00:30:26,535 --> 00:30:28,620
And water, so...

243
00:30:31,164 --> 00:30:32,165
Yeah.

244
00:30:36,128 --> 00:30:39,423
[stammers] And it does not
contain chlorine.

245
00:30:40,674 --> 00:30:41,675
So...

246
00:30:44,803 --> 00:30:46,388
Anybody listening out there?

247
00:30:46,471 --> 00:30:47,807
Huh? How about it, you 12?

248
00:30:47,890 --> 00:30:49,433
Any response?

249
00:30:50,434 --> 00:30:53,520
Are you even getting these?
'Cause how the fuck would I know?

250
00:30:58,108 --> 00:30:59,109
[camera beeps]

251
00:31:02,404 --> 00:31:03,405
[sighs]

252
00:31:11,955 --> 00:31:12,956
[screen beeps]

253
00:31:24,801 --> 00:31:26,470
[sighs]

254
00:31:30,516 --> 00:31:31,517
[camera beeps]

255
00:31:32,643 --> 00:31:34,103
Greetings, fellow survivors.

256
00:31:34,186 --> 00:31:36,313
Carol Sturka here with an update.

257
00:31:39,024 --> 00:31:41,026
{\an8}[drone whirring]

258
00:32:14,685 --> 00:32:16,687
[panting]

259
00:32:41,545 --> 00:32:43,046
[muffled thudding]

